library(ggplot2)
library(tidyverse)
library(MRIcloudT1volumetrics)
library(kirby21.mricloud)

# Use ggplot to create bar plots of year and program.
dat1 = read_tsv("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/bcaffo/ds4ph-bme/master/data/classInterests.txt")
## 
##  Column specification 
## cols(
##   Year = col_character(),
##   Program = col_character()
## )
dfsum <- dat1 %>%
    group_by(Year, Program) %>%
    tally()
gplota <- ggplot(dfsum, aes(x = Year, y = n, fill = as.factor(Program))) +
    geom_bar(stat="identity") + labs(fill="Program Type", y = "Count")+ ggtitle("Student Counts by Year")
gplota + theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1))

dfsum <- dat1 %>%
    group_by(Year, Program) %>%
    tally()
gplot <- ggplot(dfsum, aes(x = Program, y = n, fill = as.factor(Year))) +
    geom_bar(stat="identity") + labs(fill="Year", y = "Count")+ ggtitle("Student Counts By Program")

## Question 4

#Download the gene expression dataset from here. Information about the data can be found in the sample info here. From the gene expression data matrix, subtract the rowmean from each row and the column mean from each column so that you have a new matrix that has been demeaned across both rows and columns.

filename <- 'https://raw.githubusercontent.com/jhu-advdatasci/2018/master/data/GSE5859_exprs.csv'
dat <- read_csv(filename)
## Warning: Missing column names filled in: 'X1' [1]
## 
##  Column specification 
## cols(
##   .default = col_double(),
##   X1 = col_character()
## )
##  Use `spec()` for the full column specifications.
datrowname <- dat$X1
dat <- dat[,-1]
rownames(dat) <- datrowname
## Warning: Setting row names on a tibble is deprecated.
datb<- dat - rowMeans(dat)
datc <- datb - colMeans(datb)

Question 5

# Create plots of healthcare spending versus time color coded by states.
data2 <- read_csv("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/jhu-advdatasci/2018/master/data/KFF/healthcare-spending.csv", skip = 2,  n_max = 52)
## 
##  Column specification 
## cols(
##   .default = col_double(),
##   Location = col_character()
## )
##  Use `spec()` for the full column specifications.
data2 <- data2[-1,] # Take out U.S. overall spending
#data2 <- subset(data2, select = c("Location", "1991", "1995","1999","2003", "2007", "2011", "2014"))
names(data2)[2:25] <- c("1991", "1992", "1993", "1994", "1995", "1996", "1997", "1998", "1999", "2000", "2001", "2002", "2003", "2004", "2005", "2006", "2007", "2008", "2009", "2010", "2011", "2012", "2013", "2014")
long_data<- data2 %>% gather(key = "Year" , value = "Spending", c(-"Location"))
long_data$Spending=as.numeric(as.character(long_data$Spending))
long_data$Year=as.numeric(as.character(long_data$Year))
is.numeric(long_data$Spending)
## [1] TRUE
g = ggplot(long_data, aes(x = Year, y = Spending, col = Location))
g = g + geom_line() + theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust=1)) + labs(x="Year", y = "Healthcare Spending in Dollars")
g

Question 6

long_data2 <- long_data %>% group_by(Location) %>%
  summarise(SpendMean = mean(Spending)) %>% mutate(Location = as.factor(Location))
              
ggplotstate <- ggplot(long_data2, aes(x = Location, y = SpendMean)) +
    geom_bar(stat="identity") + labs(x = "State", y = "Average Spending In Dollars")+ ggtitle("Average Healthcare Spending By State")+ theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1))
ggplotstate
